Don’t these people know their Mohs scale of mineral hardness?..

36
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:01,240
Regardless,
the Romans couldn’t do this because their

37
00:02:01,239 --> 00:02:06,089
whole identity was wrapped up in an idea
of justice that precluded indiscriminate violence.

38
00:02:06,090 --> 00:02:10,950
The other strategy is to try to incorporate
conquered people into the empire more fully:

39
00:02:10,949 --> 00:02:13,149
In Rome’s case,
to make them Romans.

40
00:02:13,150 --> 00:02:15,330
This worked really well in the early days
of the Republic

41
00:02:15,330 --> 00:02:19,530
and even at the beginning of the Empire.
But it eventually led to

42
00:02:19,530 --> 00:02:21,009
Barbarians inside the Gates.

43
00:02:21,009 --> 00:02:24,810
The decline of the legions started long before
Rome started getting sacked.

44
00:02:24,810 --> 00:02:31,209
It really began with the extremely bad decision
to incorporate Germanic warriors into the Roman Army.

45
00:02:31,209 --> 00:02:35,598
Rome had a long history of absorbing people
from the empire’s fringes into the polity

46
00:02:35,598 --> 00:02:39,399
first by making them allies and then
eventually by granting them full citizenship rights.

47
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:42,740
But usually these “foreign” citizens had
developed ties to Rome itself;

48
00:02:42,750 --> 00:02:46,150
they learned Latin, they bought into the whole
idea of the aristocratic republic.

49
00:02:46,150 --> 00:02:49,209
But by the 3rd and 4th centuries CE, though,
the empire had been forced to

50
00:02:49,209 --> 00:02:53,769
allow the kind of riffraff into their army
who didn’t really care about the idea of

51
00:02:53,769 --> 00:02:56,019
Rome itself.
They were only loyal to their commanders.

52
00:02:56,019 --> 00:02:58,879
—And as you no doubt remember from the historical
examples of

53
00:02:58,878 --> 00:03:04,328
Caesar, Pompey, Marius, contemporary Afghanistan—
this is not a recipe for domestic bliss.

54
00:03:04,329 --> 00:03:07,170
So here is Rome,
stuck with a bunch of expensive and bloody

55
00:03:07,169 --> 00:03:11,188
wars against Germanic peoples who were really
good at fighting

56
00:03:11,188 --> 00:03:14,870
and then they had a great idea:
Why not fight with these guys?

57
00:03:14,870 --> 00:03:18,079
So they essentially hired them
and soon the Roman Legions were teeming with

58
00:03:18,079 --> 00:03:21,360
these mercenaries
who were loyal mostly to gold,

59
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:24,329
secondarily to their commanders,
and not at all to Rome

60
00:03:24,329 --> 00:03:27,319
which is a place that very few of them ever
even saw.

61
00:03:27,318 --> 00:03:30,199
I mean, why would they give a crap about the
health and well-being of the empire?

62
00:03:30,199 --> 00:03:32,468
Am I allowed to say crap, Stan?
Nice.

63
00:03:32,468 --> 00:03:36,789
This was of course a recipe for civil war,
and that’s exactly what happened with general

64
00:03:36,789 --> 00:03:40,438
after general after general
declaring himself Emperor of Rome.

65
00:03:40,438 --> 00:03:41,968
So there was very little stability in the
West.

66
00:03:41,968 --> 00:03:48,989
For instance, between 235 and 284 CE, 41 different
people were either emperor or claimed to be emperor.

67
00:03:48,989 --> 00:03:51,718
And after the year 200,
many of the generals who were powerful enough

68
00:03:51,718 --> 00:03:54,280
to proclaim themselves emperors weren’t
even Roman.

69
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:56,609
In fact, a lot of them didn’t speak much
Latin.

70
00:03:56,609 --> 00:04:00,719
Oddly enough, one of the best symbols of the
new face of the Roman Empire was sartorial.

71
00:04:00,718 --> 00:04:04,000
Instead of the traditional tunic and toga
of the glory days of the Senate,

72
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,139
most of the new general-emperors adopted that
most practical and most barbaric of garments: pants.

73
00:04:10,139 --> 00:04:12,479
Oh, which reminds me,
it’s time for the Open Letter.

74
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:17,800
An Open Letter to Pants:

75
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:20,280
